**Why it works**: `auth.mode = "none"` → `authorizeGatewayConnect()` returns `{ ok: true }` unconditionally → `resolveGatewayRequestedOperatorScopes()` sees no `x-openclaw-scopes` header → returns all 5 CLI_DEFAULT_OPERATOR_SCOPES → full admin access granted.","severity":"high"}

{"valid":true,"title":"ECS-Controlled `disableSandbox` + `runtimeUrls` Enables Unsandboxed Arbitrary Script Execution in HydraPlayer iframe","summary":"## Vulnerability: Unsandboxed iframe with ECS-Controlled Script URLs in Teams HydraPlayer

The `ee()` function (line 25881 of `calling_electron_bundle.js`) creates the iframe that hosts the HydraPlayer runtime. When the `disableSandbox` parameter is truthy, the `sandbox` attribute is **never set** on the iframe — meaning the iframe runs with no sandbox restrictions at all. This flag is sourced from `this.configProvider.config.hlsSettings.disableSandbox` (line 13038) or `this.configProvider.config.umsSettings.disableSandbox` (line 7802), which are populated via `mergeWith(this.defaultSettings, e, d)` where `e` comes from the ECS (Experimentation and Configuration Service) configuration fetched from `https://config.teams.microsoft.com` or `https://a.config.skype.com`. The ECS config is parsed via `getString("MDN_MIDDLELANE_TEAMS", "liveStream")` and JSON-parsed into the settings object — including the `disableSandbox` flag — with no validation or type-checking of the incoming value.

